<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pryor Facing More Legal Trouble  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ailing comedian Richard Pryor faces more
legal complications.
</P>
<P>
   Loud Records of Delaware has asked a Los Angeles Superior Court
judge to determine who owns the rights to master recordings of some
of Pryor's performances.
</P>
<P>
   Loud claims it paid $200,000 for the material in 1998 in an
agreement with a company called Found Money Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor says he owns the masters.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Pryor took out a restraining order against his
38-year-old son, Richard Jr. The move followed a court request by
Pryor's son to become conservator of his father's estate.
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old comic is fighting multiple sclerosis, and his
son claims his father cannot care for himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
