<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surprise snow blankets April flowers in NYC  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- You could almost see the tulips shivering as a
surprise snowstorm blanketed New York City Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Just a day earlier, the sun was shining, flowers bloomed from
every windowbox, and the parks were filled with kids playing the
first Little League and soccer games of spring. The temperature
Saturday reached 71 degrees in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   But by Sunday morning, the mercury dipped just below freezing
and the air was filled with snowflakes. Although less than a
half-inch accumulated, daffodils sagged under the weight of the
snow, pink cherry blossoms were frosted white and the last ice
skaters of the season looked perfectly at home at the Rockefeller
Center rink.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Randall of Brooklyn had invited neighbors to join her
and her three children at the beach at Jacob Riis Park in Queens
Sunday for an afternoon of picnicking and ball games.
</P>
<P>
   ''My beach party is not happening because of the weather,'' she
said glumly. ''We were all set to go. We had all our beach stuff
ready and it snowed.''
</P>
<P>
   The lousy weather forced the Mets to postpone their game with
the Los Angeles Dodgers. It was rescheduled for April 24.
</P>
<P>
   The snow tapered off by mid-afternoon, but windy conditions of
up to 45 mph kept the day from turning balmy. Better weather was
expected Monday with sunny skies and temperatures in the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Blossom-lovers needn't fret too much unless the weather gets
much colder, according to Karl Lauby, spokesman for the New York
Botanical Garden in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as the temperature doesn't drop below the upper 20s,
this snow and the moisture via the snow is fine for the plants,''
he said. ''Actually when it snows, the flowers may fare better than
if it were a heavy rain, which might pelt the blooms.''
</P>
<P>
   It's peak bloom time for daffodils, magnolias and cherry trees
right now, Lauby said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said the Sanitation Department had sent
out several hundred salting-and-sanding trucks to keep streets from
freezing over. ''This is an unexpected storm,'' he said. ''If you
see a sanitation worker out there, why don't you say thank you?
These are difficult conditions to be working under.''
</P>
<P>
   Newark Airport reported 20-minute delays, LaGuardia had delays
of up to 90 minutes and Kennedy experienced no delays due to the
storm.
</P>
<P>
   Normal local temperatures for this time of year range from from
42 to 59 degrees, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
