<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Sick pay deals could cost taxpayers $1 billion  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) -- Years of generous deals struck in
closed-door contract negotiations have given almost every
government worker in New Jersey a share of unused sick and vacation
day payouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Record of Hackensack reported in Sunday's editions that an
examination of 50 municipal, county and school audits -- the only
public documents in which the liability is disclosed -- show that
the payouts are now worth more than $1 billion statewide.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper said Hackensack, which limited the benefit for
employees hired since the 1980s, has paid out almost $1 million in
two years and is still obligated to pay $10.9 million to workers as
they retire.
</P>
<P>
   Lodi has a long-term obligation of $7.9 million, at a cost of
$1,241 per homeowner; and Clifton owes a total of $14 million, at a
cost of $475 per homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   The benefit is almost unheard of in private industry. But local
officials and union representatives defend the payouts as a way to
keep experienced workers and reward people who come to work daily.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do we support this concept? Yes, we do,'' said Karen Joseph, a
spokeswoman for the New Jersey Education Association. She added
that private sector employers offer their workers matching
contributions for 401(k) plans and often have stock options and
other rewards unavailable in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayer advocates and business associations disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not something that was intended to be a benefit or a
windfall when you retire,'' said Jeff Stoler, a vice president at
the New Jersey Business and Industry Association. ''Companies
provide these days so people can stay home and get well when
they're sick and take a vacation every year and come back to work
refreshed and rested.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hackensack city attorney Richard Salkin said municipal
workers have come to expect the benefit as part of their job.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a vested right,'' he said. ''We may not like it, but you
can't just take it away from people.''
</P>
<P>
   A report by the State Commission of Investigation, an
independent watchdog agency funded by the state Legislature,
detailed numerous abuses in the way pensions and retirement
benefits are awarded.
</P>
<P>
   The report in particular criticized ''excessive lump-sum
payments'' that often exceed a full year's salary and the practice
of allowing top administrators to keep track of the sick days they
use.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials have said they see no cause for alarm. They
argue that the debt listed is only an estimate of the value of
unused sick and vacation days that employees would be owed if they
all retired at once or if the government went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout northern New Jersey, payouts are being doled out
at the same time towns struggle to pay for essential services and
equipment without raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Pompton Lakes voters a few years ago rejected a $339,000 school
tax increase, prompting a special grant from the Legislature to
save the high school marching band and music classes.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the borough council refused the fire chief's
requests to replace an aging fire truck -- financed eventually by a
referendum in 1997. Meanwhile, Pompton Lakes officials approved
school and municipal labor contracts that continued to allow for
sick and vacation payouts at retirement. In 1997, that debt totaled
about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   In her annual address to the state Legislature in 1998, Gov.
Christie Whitman criticized the payouts as ''taxpayer-funded golden
parachutes'' and said they should be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, lawmakers have made several aborted attempts to cap
sick time payouts to local government and school employees at
$15,000, but by the end of the legislative term in January, none of
the bills had even been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as I'm concerned, this is a total rape of the
taxpayers,'' said Shirley Feldman, president of the Bergen County
Taxpayers Coalition. ''As long as the taxpayers continue to elect
the same public officials who are in the hip pockets of the unions,
nothing will change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
