<HEADLINE> Extreme wrestling promoters say they will self-regulate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- In an effort to forestall a legislative ban
on their ultra-violent sport, promoters of ''extreme wrestling''
said they are washing most of the blood out of their shows.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to continue doing this, and in order to continue we
need to change,'' Jeff Shapiro, co-owner of Jersey All-Pro, told
The Star-Ledger of Newark in Sunday's editions. ''We don't need the
state to come in and regulate us. We got the message loud and
clear.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was a toned-down show in Bayonne on Friday, although
emcee Fat Frank Iadavaia promised the crowd, ''there will be blood
in Charity Hall tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   There was some blood, but the machetes, cheese graters and
barbed wire were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman and Bayonne Mayor Joseph Doria, who is
also the minority leader of the Assembly, in March formed a
bipartisan coalition on the entertainment events, which they
denounced as dangerous and too gruesome for children.
</P>
<P>
   It was Whitman who enacted a change in law in 1997 to deregulate
so-called ''pro wrestling'' so that sponsors like the World
Wrestling Federation would be willing to stage TV events at New
Jersey facilities without regulation and taxes from the State
Athletic Control Board.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF has distanced itself from extreme wrestling, lauding the
governor's move to regulate the events and excusing two of its own
wrestlers from an autograph session for Jersey All-Pro next week.
</P>
<P>
   And Lowlife Louis Ramos, the ''Suicidal Title'' holder known for
bringing a machete and a willingness to bleed in the ring, has been
told to tone down his act.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been blamed for all this,'' he told the newspaper. ''I've
been ostracized in the wrestling community. I've been killed on the
(Internet) message boards. It's like I'm a scapegoat for a lot of
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
