<HEADLINE> Fraternity house fire victims died of smoke inhalation; two hadbeen drinking  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) -- The three Bloomsburg University
students killed in a fraternity house fire last month died of smoke
inhalation, and two of them had been drinking, the county coronor
said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims -- Marcus LaBuda, 22, of Hazleton; Kristoffer
Polhemus, 22, of Hampton, N.J.; and Cliff Vail, 21, of Dunellen,
N.J. -- were likely overcome by carbon monoxide and never awakened,
Columbia County Coroner Dr. Michael Kenny told The Times-Leader of
Wilkes-Barre.
</P>
<P>
   Toxicology tests on LaBuda and Polhemus indicated blood-alcohol
levels of 0.09 percent, less than the 0.10 percent at which the
state considers an adult driver intoxicated, Kenny said. He said he
could not say how that might have affected the victims' ability to
react to the March 19 fire.
</P>
<P>
   Tests on Vail were not available. No drugs were found in the
systems of the other two victims, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire at the Tau Kappa Epsilon fraternity house near the
Bloomsburg University campus broke out at 6 a.m., a few hours after
the end of a party attended by about 30 people. Three other
fraternity brothers escaped, two jumping to safety from the
second-floor window of the burning house, which was reduced to
rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the fire has not been determined, but Bloomsburg
Police Sgt. Joe Wondoloski said findings could be released next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred tearful students, friends, and family members
attended last month's funerals for the three students, whom
University President Jessica Kozloff called ''three shining stars''
of the university.
</P>
<P>
   The university plans to require at least some students to take
classes on fire prevention, and school and town officials are
looking for other ways to make off-campus housing safer.
</P>
<P>
   Another Bloomsburg fraternity house fire killed five students on
Oct. 21, 1994. A smoldering sofa was blamed for that blaze.
Batteries had been taken out of smoke detectors in the Beta Sigma
Delta house, a common practice during smoky parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
