<HEADLINE> 'American Beauty' Wins Awards  </HEADLINE>
By MATT WOLF, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- ''American Beauty,'' the darling of last month's
Oscars, was the big winner again Sunday at the Orange British
Academy Awards, taking six prizes including best picture.
</P>
<P>
   ''American Beauty'' stars Kevin Spacey and Annette Bening were
named best actor and actress, but the film's Oscar-winning director
Sam Mendes was beaten for the best director award by Spanish
filmmaker Pedro Almodovar for ''All About My Mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Caine was an also-ran for best supporting actor but
collected a lifetime achievement award from the British Academy of
Film and Television Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The awards were called the Orange British Academy Awards because
of sponsorship by a mobile telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's ceremony was a mix of Oscar winners reprising
their triumphs -- ''American Beauty'' cinematographer Conrad L.
Hall, for instance -- and Oscar also-rans such as 27-year-old Jude
Law, who was best supporting actor for ''The Talented Mr. Ripley.''
</P>
<P>
   The supporting actress prize went to Dame Maggie Smith for ''Tea
with Mussolini,'' a film that was entirely overlooked by the
American Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting her prize, Smith thanked veterans co-stars Judi Dench
and Joan Plowright for ''hours of Scrabble and gallons of Frescati
(wine).''
</P>
<P>
   The alcohol theme was picked up by Spacey, who complimented
BAFTA organizers for providing champagne and chocolates for every
guest. ''I've been drinking all night,'' said Spacey, adding that
the occasion was less nerve-wracking than the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   Mena Suvari, who played the object of Spacey's affection,
accepted the award for Bening, who stayed at home because of her
advanced pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ''American Beauty'' had led all comers with 14 BAFTA
nominations, followed by ''The End of the Affair'' and ''The
Talented Mr. Ripley'' with 10 and seven nominations respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Caine drew the evening's greatest ovation when he accepted the
BAFTA Fellowship, as the lifetime achievement award is known.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm getting used to standing ovations; I like it,'' Caine
cracked.
</P>
<P>
   But his speech turned serious when he admitted that recognition
in his home country has been a long time in coming. ''I never
really felt like I belonged in my own country, or my own
profession. It's an honor to be invited in from the cold,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A second ovation greeted Christiane Kubrick, who accepted a
BAFTA Fellowship for her husband Stanley Kubrick, the reclusive
British-based American director who died last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not know who would be here if Stanley had lived -- to
appear in public was not his best thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar was an enthusiastic winner, also taking honors for
best film not in the English language.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you want me to have a heart attack?'' Almodovar said after
the second prizes. ''It seems to me I'm having a honeymoon with the
British audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Oscars, the BAFTAs include an award for most popular
film, voted by filmgoers. That produced the only award of the night
for ''Notting Hill,'' the biggest-grossing British film of all
time.
</P>
<P>
   The eclectic lineup of presenters included Faye Dunaway, ''Naked
Gun'' star Leslie Nielsen and Dustin Hoffman, who was in fine comic
form.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling his trip in from the airport, Hoffman told the
audience: ''I had a wonderful cab driver and his name is Dave, and
he said to give him a mention ... so cheers, Dave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
