<HEADLINE> Snow, frigid winds trap hikers, cause accidents, power outages  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFORD TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- A spring snowstorm surprised New
Jersey on Sunday, knocking out power to thousands of homes, causing
dozens of fender-benders on icy, snow-covered roads and endangering
campers unprepared for the sudden change of weather.
</P>
<P>
   Four hikers were rescued Sunday morning from the Appalachian
Trail in Stokes State Forest in the highlands of northwestern New
Jersey, where they had taken shelter overnight at an open-air
lean-to at about 1200 feet elevation, according to state Department
of Environmental Protection officials.
</P>
<P>
   ''They got taken by surprise by the storm,'' said DEP
spokeswoman Sharon Southard. ''They probably had incorrect attire
for this weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures across the Garden State hit the mid-70s Saturday
afternoon, then plunged early Sunday to the low 30s -- with fierce
winds pushing the wind chill to the single digits early in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Two rangers summoned Sunday morning by Boy Scouts to the Brink
Shelter, a camping area on Kittatiny Ridge along the Appalachian
Trail, found about 100 hikers waiting there. They included a group
of 80 teen-agers, young adults and chaperones from the Monmouth
Council of Boy Scouts and another 20 from Plainfield Boy Scout
Troop 235.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the Scouts were believed to have hypothermia, or low
body temperature, Southard said. It was unclear if the four had
stayed in the lean-to overnight or had tents.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Plainfield Scouts were carried down the mountain to
a waiting ambulance, and one of the Monmouth Scouts was helped down
on foot. All four were treated at the scene by personnel from the
Blue Ridge Rescue Squad.
</P>
<P>
   Their names were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state forest rangers checked on more than 200 other
campers who were in the park in Sussex County this weekend, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody seems to be all right,'' Southard said.
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern New Jersey was hardest hit by the storm, with High
Point getting 7{ inches of snow by late morning, according to Bob
Stauber, a National Weather Service meteorologist in Mount Laurel.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas barely got a trace of snow -- the Atlantic City
airport received just 0.2 inches and Toms River got 0.5 inches.
Meanwhile, Gloucester and Cumberland counties received 2 inches of
snow, Burlington County got more than 3 inches, Trenton got 4,
Hackettstown in Warren County received 5.5 inches and communities
in Sussex County got 4 inches to 7.5 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year around this date it snowed also,'' Stauber noted.
''So it's nowhere near a record'' to have snow this far into
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The snow petered out by early afternoon, but the wind didn't. A
high wind advisory for the whole state and a gale warning for the
coast were in effect all day.
</P>
<P>
   Gusts of 39 mph were reported at the airports in Newark and
Teterboro in the afternoon, but by then the sun was out, pushing
the mercury to 40 degrees and melting most of the snow.
</P>
<P>
   State police reported treacherous driving conditions in the
morning, mainly across North Jersey, caused dozens of
fender-benders, but no serious accidents.
</P>
<P>
   However, vehicles sliding into utility poles and trees toppled
by wind gusts tore down power lines, leaving more than 6,500
customers without electricity at some point Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had widely scattered outages,'' said GPU Energy
spokesman Ron Morano. ''Many of these outages are due to car-pole
accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Morano said about 6,000 customers were without power at midday,
in Warren, Sussex and Morris counties in northern New Jersey and
Hunterdon, Ocean and Monmouth counties in central New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not anything where people are going to be out of service
for a long time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Public Service Electric &AMP; Gas Co. said about 75 customers in
Verona and East and West Orange in Essex County were without
electricity since about 10 a.m. because of a downed power line;
service was expected to be back by early evening. About 500
customers in Willingboro who were without electricity for about
three hours Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The snow caused minor delays early in the day at Newark
International Airport, which received 1 inch of snow, according to
police with the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. Bridges,
tunnels and trains linking New York and New Jersey were unaffected,
and NJ Transit reported no problems.
</P>
<P>
   The snow did force postponement of Sunday's game between the
Trenton Thunder and the New Haven Ravens.
</P>
</TEXT>
