<HEADLINE> Courts, not sex offenders, new enemy in battle for Megan's Law  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Forget the image of Jesse Timmendequas, the
twice-convicted sex offender living across the street.
</P>
<P>
   For supporters of Megan's Law, the latest bogeymen wear black
robes.
</P>
<P>
   ''When Megan's Law was adopted, I don't think anybody foresaw
what the courts would do to it,'' said Lee Solomon, the Camden
County prosecutor who was a member of the Legislature when the law
was passed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's time to stand up to the courts,'' said
Assemblyman Joel Weingarten, R-Essex, whose bill to post sex
offenders' names on the Internet would likely need a constitutional
amendment before it could become law.
</P>
<P>
   Even Maureen Kanka is pointing a finger at the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem doesn't lie with the Legislature. It lies with the
judges,'' Megan's mother said. ''We are constantly hampered by the
courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The criticism comes as state lawmakers look to spread the
community notifications allowed by Megan's Law well beyond the
narrow bounds so far set by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Weingarten's bill passed 55 to 0 in the Assembly, with 17
abstentions. The vote came the same day the Whitman administration
announced it wants a constitutional amendment to allow the state to
post information about sex offenders on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's amendment would allow anyone who has access to the
Internet to see a sex offender's name, address and photo as well as
a description of the crimes committed. Any amendment must be passed
by both houses in the Legislature and then by voters.
</P>
<P>
   Without that amendment, many say Weingarten's bill and any other
measure to broaden Megan's Law would be struck down by the courts.
Others contend any new amendment will still run afoul of the U.S.
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Timmendequas raped and murdered Megan Kanka in July 1994
and is awaiting execution on death row. Residents in their Hamilton
Township neighborhood said his prior sex crimes were unknown to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Megan's Law was ''measured against the U.S. Constitution, then
found deficient,'' said lawyer William H. Buckman. State and
federal judges were balancing ''the rights we all have'' against
the law's intentions and its implications, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What concerns me is that they have no concerns whatsoever
about the Constitution, and no concerns about the Constitution that
protects everybody,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Courts must look beyond information about sex offenders and
consider if the Whitman amendment might allow the state to post any
type of record -- criminal, financial or personal -- it keeps,
Buckman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could one-day become a high-tech scarlet letter society,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers say they are frustrated by the fact that New Jersey
passed the first Megan's Law but other states seem to be able to do
more, like post names on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is the courts that supervise New Jersey have meddled
in the process, Weingarten said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we need to move away from an active judiciary and one
that attempts to engage in the legislative process,'' Weingarten
said. He claims the bill can withstand a review by the federal
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the state's Megan's Law groups convicted sex
offenders into three levels based on the perceived danger the felon
presents. For those labeled most at risk of committing another
crime, the law allows prosecutors to provide an offender's name,
address and photo to residents living in a carefully defined area.
All offenders are required to register with police once out of
prison.
</P>
<P>
   But much of how the law works now -- judicial review of the
notification, a scoring system for offenses, -- was ordered not by
the Legislature, but by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in January said New Jersey law enforcement
authorities routinely allowed private information about sex
offenders to become widely public during community notifications.
The judge ordered the state to revise its regulations or shut down
the system. The attorney general then released new guidelines
requiring people who receive notices to promise to keep the
information secret.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, U.S. District Judge Joseph Irenas again heard
arguments from the state public defender's office that the new
guidelines were faulty.
</P>
<P>
   Irenas issued no ruling, but he praised the attorney general for
his work, calling the new notification guidelines ''a decent, legal
reaction to the decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
